          <div class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a></div>                              <h2>Dear Rebel</h2>                                                  <div class="clear-block">
            <div id="node-21" class="node">



  
  <div class="content clear-block">
    <p>Chivers Large print<br />
Hardback 2007, ISBN 978 1 405 64230 9<br />
Softback 2008, ISBN 978 1 405 64231 6<br />
&nbsp;</p>
<p><img hspace="10" vspace="10" align="left" src="/sites/default/files/Dear%20Rebel_0.jpg" width="100" height="161" />Like many men in his position, Lord Carthorne was more concerned with protecting Waterlea Manor in the fens of East Anglia that taking sides in the war between Charles I and Parliament. He had no hesitation in using the childhood betrothal of his daughter Alys and Cromwell's captain, Sir Garret Hartswood, to achieve this. It was an enormous shock to Alys who had forgotten the betrothal and was a fervent Cavalier to boot. There seemed no escape from Garret's determination to honour the agreement&hellip;</p>  </div>

